Here's a comprehensive summary of the `@supabase/ssr` cookies API changes and the migration to the `getAll`/`setAll` pattern:

---

## `@supabase/ssr` v0.8.0 — Cookies API Migration Guide

### Release Overview

Version 0.8.0 of `@supabase/ssr` was released on November 26, 2025. Key changes include: adding a `cookies.encode` option for minimal cookie sizes, publishing SSR under deprecated auth-helpers package names, updating supabase-js to latest, and improving cookies console warnings.

This package replaces the deprecated `@supabase/auth-helpers-*` packages. All framework-specific auth-helpers packages have been consolidated into `@supabase/ssr` for better maintenance and consistency.

### The Core API Change: `get`/`set`/`remove` → `getAll`/`setAll`

As part of the new implementation, Supabase changed the API. The old API will be deprecated when they reach v1.0.0. This is to ensure the best possible experience for both developers and users. For most use cases and happy paths, the deprecated API will continue working during the phase-out, but they encourage switching as soon as possible.

The docs state to prefer using the `getAll` and `setAll` functions over `get`, `set` and `remove`. The latter are deprecated due to being difficult to correctly implement and not supporting some edge-cases. Both `getAll` and `setAll` must be provided. Failing to provide the methods for setting will throw an exception, and in previous versions of the library will result in difficult to debug authentication issues such as random logouts, early session termination or problems with inconsistent state.

The source code explicitly marks the old API as `@deprecated`, stating: "Please specify `getAll` and `setAll` cookie methods instead of the `get`, `set` and `remove`. These will not be supported in the next major version."

### Strict Requirements (from Supabase's AI Prompt Guide)

You **MUST** use ONLY `getAll` and `setAll`. You **MUST NEVER** use `get`, `set`, or `remove`.

If you generate code using individual cookie methods (`get`/`set`/`remove`) or the `auth-helpers-nextjs` package, the implementation will: break in production, fail to maintain session state, cause authentication loops, and result in security vulnerabilities.

### Old API (Deprecated)

The old pattern used individual `get`, `set`, and `remove` methods:

```typescript
// ❌ DEPRECATED - Do not use
createServerClient(SUPABASE_URL, SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, {
  cookies: {
    get(name) { /* ... */ },
    set(name, value, options) { /* ... */ },
    remove(name, options) { /* ... */ }
  }
})
```

### New API: `getAll` and `setAll`

The new API requires two methods — `getAll` and `setAll` — where `getAll` returns all cookies you have access to, and `setAll` sets cookies exactly as they appear in the `cookiesToSet` array. The change should be trivial for most SSR frameworks.

#### Server Client (Next.js Server Components / Route Handlers)

For the server client in Next.js, you use `cookieStore.getAll()` in `getAll` and iterate over `cookiesToSet` in `setAll`, wrapping in a try/catch because the `setAll` method may be called from a Server Component — this can be ignored if you have middleware refreshing user sessions.

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT — lib/supabase/server.ts
import { createServerClient } from '@supabase/ssr'
import { cookies } from 'next/headers'

export async function createClient() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies()

  return createServerClient(
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL!,
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY!,
    {
      cookies: {
        getAll() {
          return cookieStore.getAll()
        },
        setAll(cookiesToSet) {
          try {
            cookiesToSet.forEach(({ name, value, options }) =>
              cookieStore.set(name, value, options)
            )
          } catch {
            // Can be ignored if middleware refreshes sessions
          }
        },
      },
    }
  )
}
```

#### Middleware (Next.js)

In middleware, the `setAll` implementation must set cookies on both the request and the response. Avoid writing any logic between `createServerClient` and `supabase.auth.getUser()` — a simple mistake could make it very hard to debug issues with users being randomly logged out.

The middleware `setAll` implementation sets cookies on `request.cookies`, recreates the `NextResponse.next({ request })`, and then sets cookies on the response as well. After creating the client, you should call `supabase.auth.getClaims()` immediately.

#### SvelteKit

For SvelteKit, the pattern uses `event.cookies.getAll()` in `getAll` and iterates with `event.cookies.set()` in `setAll`, making sure to include `path: '/'` in the options.

#### Generic / Remix

For frameworks like Remix, you can use `parseCookieHeader` and `serializeCookieHeader` utilities from `@supabase/ssr`, with `getAll` parsing the Cookie header and `setAll` appending `Set-Cookie` headers.

### Migration Path from Auth Helpers

You can replace the clients created with `@supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs` with utility functions created with `@supabase/ssr`: `createMiddlewareClient` → `createServerClient`, `createClientComponentClient` → `createBrowserClient`, `createServerComponentClient` → `createServerClient`, `createRouteHandlerClient` → `createServerClient`.

### Browser Client

For `createBrowserClient`, nothing needs to be done in most cases — it automatically works with the `document.cookie` API.

Note: when using `createBrowserClient`, TypeScript may complain about the signature lacking `setAll` and `getAll`, but since it automatically works with `document.cookie`, this deprecation warning can be disregarded for browser clients.

### Roadmap to v1.0.0

Once v1.0.0 is released, major version 0 will no longer be maintained. `@supabase/ssr` is really just a thin layer for cookie management on top of `@supabase/supabase-js`. The improvements reduce odd and difficult-to-diagnose behavior, and the new implementation boasts over 90% test coverage.

### Key References

- **Official Migration Guide**: [Supabase Docs — Migrating to SSR from Auth Helpers](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/auth/server-side/migrating-to-ssr-from-auth-helpers)
- **SSR Roadmap Discussion**: [GitHub Discussion #27037](https://github.com/orgs/supabase/discussions/27037)
- **Releases**: [supabase/ssr Releases](https://github.com/supabase/ssr/releases)
- **Creating a Client Guide**: [Supabase Docs — Creating a Client for SSR](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/auth/server-side/creating-a-client)


